	<item>
		<title>Comment on Furniture by Billy</title>
		<link>http://lifeandmusic.loricarson.com/?p=99#comment-452</link>
		<dc:creator>Billy</dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 22 Jul 2010 15:52:11 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://lifeandmusic.loricarson.com/?p=99#comment-452</guid>
		<description>Hi Kiddo,
There is definately something magical about that table. I met you over it. Had coffee and some of the best conversation I&#039;ve had to date, watching you across it under the dim and dimming light of the faux-candle chandalere that still hangs above where that table used to sit. I wrote parts of my latest and still incomplete novel at that table ... Ate countless meals there ... Thought of your Father, the angle master and the many moves he&#039;d seen it through ... But mostly ... I thought of you. You warned me about the whole haunting thing ... Cori Larson peeking out from every dimly-lit corner, giggling and coaxing me to give chase. And the mystic energy you left there for me continues to make my writing and my music come without effort in a way it  never did before &quot;Yellow House&quot; had the first page written. I picked up a place out on Nassau Point ... Still further East than your old place ... I&#039;ll move there eventually. It&#039;s huge. 5 bedrooms ... Silly ... I&#039;ll only use one, just like at your place ... But I like the roominess of it ... Not quite ON the water, but just 7 houses away. And a big, brick fireplace. I&#039;ll more than likely live there alone for a time ... Perhaps a very long time. A dear friend once told me to cherish my solitude and that it would be there that my music and prose would grow. I&#039;m taking her advice.

Forever,
Billy
Post Script:
November ... Coffee or Veggie Thai ... You pick, I&#039;ll pay. I miss you.</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Hi Kiddo,<br />
There is definately something magical about that table. I met you over it. Had coffee and some of the best conversation I&#8217;ve had to date, watching you across it under the dim and dimming light of the faux-candle chandalere that still hangs above where that table used to sit. I wrote parts of my latest and still incomplete novel at that table &#8230; Ate countless meals there &#8230; Thought of your Father, the angle master and the many moves he&#8217;d seen it through &#8230; But mostly &#8230; I thought of you. You warned me about the whole haunting thing &#8230; Cori Larson peeking out from every dimly-lit corner, giggling and coaxing me to give chase. And the mystic energy you left there for me continues to make my writing and my music come without effort in a way it  never did before &#8220;Yellow House&#8221; had the first page written. I picked up a place out on Nassau Point &#8230; Still further East than your old place &#8230; I&#8217;ll move there eventually. It&#8217;s huge. 5 bedrooms &#8230; Silly &#8230; I&#8217;ll only use one, just like at your place &#8230; But I like the roominess of it &#8230; Not quite ON the water, but just 7 houses away. And a big, brick fireplace. I&#8217;ll more than likely live there alone for a time &#8230; Perhaps a very long time. A dear friend once told me to cherish my solitude and that it would be there that my music and prose would grow. I&#8217;m taking her advice.</p>
